{
  "text": "This study identified femoral head osteophytes in 8 (53%) out of 15 hips at the mean 53-months follow-up. There were no cases where the joint space narrowed, but a proper evaluation will require a longer follow-up period. Saito et al. 17) emphasized the importance of the fixation materials in minimizing the occurrence of complications from a transtrochanteric rotational osteotomy, such as the fractured neck of the femur caused by postoperative stress, delayed the union of the portions treated with an osteotomy and varus deformity. According to Kotz [CITATION_1] , Mizuho Ika's large screws or the USA's screws are more useful for fixation than A-O compression hip screws. Sugioka also preferred large screws 19) . It is believed that, because gradually introducing weight bearing is essential for remodeling and can prevent the newly created cartilage from degenerating, this gradual burdening is very important even though a strong internal fixation instrument might be required.",
  "citation_candidates": [
    "40097362",
